article.description: Eddie Jones scored 18 points and Mike James added eight of his season-high 14 in the fourth quarter as the Miami Heat dominated the sluggish Lakers en route to a 97-85 victory.
article.headline: Lakers lose first game since Shaq's return
article.linkText: Heat send Lakers to first loss since Shaq's return
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal was rusty, Kobe Bryant fought foul trouble and the Miami Heat played like anything but a last-place team.
Jones

O'Neal was only ordinary in his third game back from toe surgery, scoring 15 points as Miami won for only the third time this season, beating the Los Angeles Lakers 97-85 Tuesday night. "To beat anybody right now is big for us,'' said Eddie Jones, who led the Heat with 18 points. "It so happened it was the world champions. We'll take it.'' Reserves Mike James and LaPhonso Ellis sparked the Heat (3-10), who came into the game tied for last place in the Atlantic Division. James scored 14 points and Ellis 13, and both sank key 3-pointers in the fourth quarter. The Lakers fell to 2-1 since O'Neal's return. Without him they were 3-9, their worst start in 36 years. "We're not connecting with each other,'' coach Phil Jackson said. "It's obvious we haven't had enough time with Shaq to have the continuity or the flow.'' "It's a matter of getting our rhythm back,'' Bryant said. "Shaq is going to get his rhythm back.'' Bryant, averaging 42 minutes per game, was limited to 32 because of foul trouble and scored 21 points. He was accidentally kicked in the right shin with 22 seconds left and departed for the dressing room, but he's expected to play Wednesday at Orlando. O'Neal played a season-high 32 minutes but was too rusty to take advantage of the Heat's undersized front line. He missed 10 of 15 shots, including an uncontested layup and an alley-oop dunk. He was in midseason form only with his free-throw shooting, going 5-for-9. O'Neal didn't talk to reporters after the game. "He didn't have the same bounce tonight that he had in the other two games,'' teammate Derek Fisher said. "The energy just wasn't there. It only makes sense that after a while, the adrenaline isn't going to be there where it was before. It's tough for him right now to do this night after night, but he'll get there.'' O'Neal and Bryant each sat for 16 minutes, and the Lakers bench was outscored 36-8 by Heat reserves. "I never said we were the deepest team in the world,'' Bryant said. Los Angeles committed 21 turnovers, missed 12 of 15 3-point shots and lost its sixth road game in a row. The Heat snapped a three-game losing streak and won for the first time in their past six home games. James' 3-pointer put the Heat up by 13 for the first time, 82-69 with 6:30 left, and he sank another 3-pointer to make it 85-71. When the Lakers cut a 16-point deficit to 87-78 with 3:18 to go, Ellis stymied the comeback. He sank a 3-pointer that bounced high off the rim before falling through the net as he hopped up the court in jubilant celebration. The Heat matched their season-high point total and surpassed 80 for the first time in four games. "Maybe it's a breakthrough for us,'' coach Pat Riley said. "We're a heart team and a hustle team; we just can't make any shots. We're a horrible offensive team. It's nice when some shots go in.'' Miami shot 60 percent in the opening 15 minutes to go ahead 38-27. Ellis capped a 23-9 Heat spurt with back-to-back 3-pointers, only his third and fourth of the season, and the Heat led the rest of the way. With Bryant limited to nine minutes in the first half because of foul trouble, Los Angeles trailed 50-41 at halftime. The Lakers cut the deficit to 62-57 midway through the third quarter, then failed to score on their next four possessions as the margin grew to 11.

Game notes
Miami's Caron Butler leads NBA rookies in minutes and is second in scoring, assists, 3-point percentage and free throw percentage. ... O'Neal said he hopes Miami's Alonzo Mourning is cautious about trying to come back from his battle with a kidney disease. "I think if it's going to put a danger on his real life, he should retire,'' O'Neal said. "He's one of the greatest centers I ever played with -- probably the greatest. I want to see him down the road 20 years from now, not trying to play and get a championship, taking all these pills and messing up your kidneys, and one day it could be gone.'' ... The Lakers fell to 0-8 when they trail at halftime.
